<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<worksheet>
  <title>Homework 03</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      <alert>Instructions:</alert> Complete all the exercises below and submit your work via 
      <url href="https://www.gradescope.com/courses/1238540">Gradescope</url> by Monday February 16 at 10pm.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <page>
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Complete one of the following tasks: either (a) read Ted Chiang's short story 
                <url href="https://myenglishhomework.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/03/tower_of_babylon_-_ted_chiang.pdf">Tower of Babylon</url> 
                and write one-page description of the topology of the story's world, or (b) write a one-page description of some other 
                real or imagined object with a novel topology. Your description should, at minimum, include both the quotient and 
                product topologies.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <statement>
            <p>
              Prove <xref ref="prop-quotient-unique" />: If <m>(Z,\tau)</m> and <m>(Z,\tau')</m> are topologies on 
              <m>Z</m> satisfying the universal property of <xref ref="def-quotient-top" />, then <m>\tau=\tau'</m>.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                In this problem, you will determine the homeomorphism type of some quotients of the plane.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              For points <m>(x_0,y_0),(x_1,y_1)\in \mathbb R^2</m>, declare
              <md>
                (x_0,y_0)\sim (x_1,y_1)\iff x_0+y_0^2=x_1+y_1^2.
              </md>
              Endow <m>\mathbb R^2/\sim</m> with the quotient topology and determine, with proof, a familiar space with which it is 
              homeomorphic.
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Do the same thing again but with
              <md>
                (x_0,y_0)\sim (x_1,y_1)\iff x_0^2+y_0^2=x_1^2+y_1^2.
              </md>
            </p>
          </statement>
        </task>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>X,Y</m> be spaces and give <m>X\times Y</m> the product topology. Prove that the projection maps <m>X\leftarrow X\times Y\to Y</m> 
          are open maps.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
    <exercise>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For a space <m>X</m> and positive integer <m>n</m>, we write
          <md>
            \operatorname{Conf}_n(X) := \{(x_1,\ldots,x_n)\in X^n\mid x_i=x_j\implies i=j\} \subseteq X^n
          </md>
          for the <term>configuration space</term> of <m>n</m> labeled points in <m>X</m>. It is endowed with the subspace topology relative to 
          <m>X^n</m>. The <term>unordered configuration space</term> of <m>n</m> points in <m>X</m> is the quotient
          <md>
            \operatorname{UConf}_n(X) := \operatorname{Conf}_n(X)/\sim
          </md>
          where <m>\mathbf x\sim \mathbf y\iff</m> the coordinates of <m>\mathbf y</m> are a permutation of the coordinates of <m>\mathbf x</m>. 
        </p>
        <p>
          (Aside: If you know about group actions, then you can note that the permutation group on <m>n</m> letters, <m>\mathfrak S_n</m>, acts on 
          <m>\operatorname{Conf}_n(X)</m> by <md>\sigma\cdot (x_1,\ldots,x_n) = (x_{\sigma 1},\ldots,x_{\sigma n}),</md> and the unordered 
          configuration space is the quotient <m>\operatorname{UConf}_n(X) = \operatorname{Conf}_n(x)/\mathfrak S_n</m>.)
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Determine the homeomorphism type of <m>\operatorname{Conf}_2(S^1)</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Do your best to describe the topology of <m>\operatorname{UConf}_2(S^1)</m>.
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Which notation do you prefer: <m>\operatorname{UConf}_n(X)</m> or <m>\binom{X}{n}</m>?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
    </exercise>

  </page>
</worksheet>
